class Solution {
public:
    string smallestSubsequence(string s) {
        int last[26] = {0};
        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            last[s[i] - 'a'] = i;
        }
        string res;
        bool vis[26] = {false};
        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            if (vis[s[i] - 'a']) continue;
            while (!res.empty() && res.back() > s[i] && last[res.back() - 'a'] > i) {
                vis[res.back() - 'a'] = false;
                res.pop_back();
            }
            res.push_back(s[i]);
            vis[s[i] - 'a'] = true;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses two passes through the string. The first pass records the last occurrence of each character. The second pass constructs the smallest subsequence by iterating through the string and adding characters to the result if they are smaller than the last character in the result and their last occurrence is later than the last character in the result.

